Subject: Web UI: unhide Resolution Scale Factor slider on Linux

Apollo's per-app config form (apps.html) gates the Resolution Scale Factor
slider with:

    <div class="mb-3" v-if="platform === 'windows'">
      <label for="resolutionScaleFactor">...</label>
      <input type="range" ... v-model="editForm['scale-factor']"/>
    </div>

So the entire slider is hidden when the host is not Windows. But the backend
plumbing for `scale-factor` is fully present in the Linux build:

    process.cpp:200  int scale_factor = launch_session->scale_factor;
    process.cpp:201  if (_app.scale_factor != 100) { scale_factor = _app.scale_factor; }
    process.cpp:205  if (scale_factor != 100) {
    process.cpp:206    render_width  *= ((float)scale_factor / 100);
    process.cpp:207    render_height *= ((float)scale_factor / 100);
    process.cpp:215  launch_session->width  = render_width;
    process.cpp:216  launch_session->height = render_height;
    process.cpp:309  VDISPLAY::createVirtualDisplay(... render_width, render_height ...);

Combined with patch 0007 (display_evdi_t reading the EVDI CPU buffer at the
configured size), supersampling works on Linux exactly like on Windows:
client requests 1280x800, scale-factor=150% renders the EVDI virtual display
at 1920x1200, encoder downscales for the wire. Sharper streams.

Fix: drop the platform === 'windows' gate. The slider now shows on Linux
(and macOS, for that matter — same backend code path).

apps.json `scale-factor` already defaults to 100 (no-op), so existing
configs are unaffected.

--- a/src_assets/common/assets/web/apps.html
+++ b/src_assets/common/assets/web/apps.html
@@ -404,7 +404,14 @@
                   default="false"
         ></Checkbox>
         <!-- resolution scale factor -->
-        <div class="mb-3" v-if="platform === 'windows'">
+        <!-- Previously gated to platform === 'windows'. The backend
+             (process.cpp:200-216) supports scale_factor on Linux too:
+             it scales render_width/height before passing them to
+             VDISPLAY::createVirtualDisplay, so the EVDI virtual display
+             is created at the supersampled resolution and downscaled by
+             the encoder for the client. Removing the platform gate so
+             Linux users can use it from the web UI. -->
+        <div class="mb-3">
           <label for="resolutionScaleFactor" class="form-label">{{ $t('apps.resolution_scale_factor') }}: {{editForm['scale-factor']}}%</label>
           <input type="range" step="1" min="20" max="200" class="form-range" id="resolutionScaleFactor" v-model="editForm['scale-factor']"/>
           <div class="form-text">{{ $t('apps.resolution_scale_factor_desc') }}</div>
